<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Schedules EU Referendum for 16 Oct </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Schedules EU Referendum for 16 Oct </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605082694 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
0600 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605082694 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The government has reached agreement on a 
national subsidy package linked to the EU [European Union] 
settlement. Uninterrupted negotiations lasting 12 hours ended 
this morning at about 0500. The government's ministerial group 
on the EU also agreed that Finland will hold a referendum on 16 
October on joining the EU, that is, before Sweden and Norway. 
  According to Prime Minister Esko Aho, the main features of 
the subsidy package are in line with a proposal drafted by a 
group of officials. The costs of the first year of the subsidy 
package will be nearly 15 billion markkas, after which they will 
then fall. The domestic subsidy for agriculture will be 5.5-6 
billion markkas a year. 
  The government's ministerial group will finalize the 
decisions on the subsidy package this morning. After that, the 
parliamentary groups of the government parties will decide on 
their stand on the solution achieved and the Council of State 
will make decisions tomorrow. 
  During the night, the government also decided on a reduced 
value-added tax on foodstuffs. Instead of the planned 22 
percent, their tax base will be 17 percent for the next three 
years. From the beginning of 1998, the tax will fall to 12 
percent. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

