<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Subsidy Seen Too Small </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Subsidy Seen Too Small </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605102594 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
0800 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Esa Haermaelae, chairman of the Central Union of 
Agricultural Producers and Forest Owners, MTK, thinks that the 
domestic EU [European Union] subsidy for agriculture is too 
small. In the subsidy package agreed by the government the 
subsidy is about 5.5-6 billion Finnish markkas [FM]. According 
to Haermaelae, the sum is much the same as that proposed by the 
working group of officials, which the MTK calculated was FM700 
too little per hectare. The MTK chairman points out that the 
subsidy of FM15 billion to be paid out in the first year of 
membership should not be seen in its entirety as an agricultural 
subsidy, because other food producers benefit from it too. 
  The government agreed on domestic subsidies for farmers and 
the foodstuffs industry during negotiations that lasted 
throughout the night. If Finland becomes a member of the EU, 
the subsidy to be paid in the first year of membership will 
total FM15 billion, which is FM4 billion more than now. In five 
years' time, the domestic subsidy to be paid out would be about 
FM6 billion a year. The increase in the agricultural subsidy 
will be compensated to the taxpayers in such a way that a 
smaller value-added tax on food than planned will be payable; 
initially 17 percent and in three years' time 12 percent. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

