<H3> <TI>   Turkey Assures UK, U.S. Governments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkey Assures UK, U.S. Governments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2605104094 Nicosia I MAKHI in Greek 26 May 94 pp 1, 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC2605104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I MAKHI </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by K. Kiriakidhis] </F>
  [Excerpt] Turkish Prime Minister Tansu Ciller assured the 
British and U.S. Governments that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf 
Denktas will finally give a positive answer on the 
confidence-building measures. 
  According to I MAKHI's information, a diplomatic source in 
Nicosia (from a country that is a permanent UN Security Council 
member) said the message has already been conveyed to the Greek 
Cypriot side to calm concerns created by the delay in the 
submission of UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's report. 
British officials believe Denktas will accept the 21 March UN 
document on the confidence-building measures and express this 
position openly. 
  During a dinner on 23 May for Greek Cypriot political 
leaders, British Deputy Foreign Secretary Tom Richardson 
revealed that at the end of the past week the Turkish side asked 
for a 10-day deadline to give Denktas the chance to "manipulate" 
his "sudden" change toward accepting the measures. The British 
official even asked the party leaders or representatives for 
their views on how the talks procedure can move to the next 
stage, that is, discussion of the substance of the Cyprus issue. 
He asked the leaders for their views on Butrus-Ghali's set of 
ideas, which the United Nations considers the basis for talks on 
the substance of the Cyprus issue. 
  According to I MAKHI, despite the assurances that the 
Cypriot 
Government received, it remains dissatisfied and disappointed 
with the supportive stance that it believes the United States is 
showing. The Greek Cypriot side believes the U.S. stance is 
encouraging Turkish intransigence and facilitating Turkish 
maneuvers. It also expresses strong concerns that Denktas will 
finally accept the confidence-building measures "with 
conditions" (something that is categorically rejected). 
  Yesterday, for the first time in public and after a week's 
delay, U.S. Ambassador in Nicosia Richard Boucher described as 
false Turkish Cypriot press reports that at the Vienna talks, 
Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department's special coordinator on 
the Cyprus issue, submitted new proposals that change the 21 
March document. I MAKHI reported yesterday that during his 
meeting with Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis the day before 
yesterday, the U.S. ambassador made the same explicit denial. 
  Speaking at the U.S. stand at the International State Fair, 
the U.S. ambassador mentioned that an effort was made in Vienna 
to understand the confidence-building measures and overcome the 
obstacles. He noted that the United States insists on 
implementing the confidence-building measures, adding that the 
ongoing efforts include studying alternative ways of action for 
accepting the package. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

