<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruehe Advocates `Broad Dialogue' With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505193594 Mainz ZDF Television Network in German 1700 GMT 
25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2505193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mainz ZDF Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Barbara Ruete report from Brussels] </F>
  [Excerpt] When the Russian defense minister entered the 
NATO building this morning, hopes were high that Russia would 
recognize the Western alliance as the supreme military and 
political body. However, in his speech at the NATO Cooperation 
Council, Grachev presented his vision. Russia would like to 
expand the CSCE to the supreme political body. In this 
roundabout way, the big power would again get a greater say in 
important decisions. This is categorically rejected by NATO. 
  [Begin Defense Minister Volker Ruehe recording] We see the 
CSCE as a roof, but what NATO is doing for stability in Europe 
cannot be replaced by the CSCE. I do not advocate that Russia 
become a NATO member, but I advocate that the Central and East 
European states can become NATO members. Regarding Russia, I 
advocate a broad dialogue, for instance also about issues that 
go beyond the Partnership for Peace. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 
  [Vienna ORF Television Network in German at 1730 GMT carries 
a similar report about the NATO meeting in Brussels, where Ruehe 
is shown as saying: "I think that Russia's position is 
justified. Who could be more interested than we are in talking 
with the Russians, for instance about nonproliferation and about 
the safety of nuclear weapons?"] 

</TEXT>

