<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Notes Albanian Foreign Ministry Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Notes Albanian Foreign Ministry Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2505192194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2505192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on an Albanian Foreign Ministry statement 
that criticizes the Greek Government for Greek minority members' 
involvement in the Greek Secret Police and other 
unconstitutional activities as well as illegal possession of 
arms, Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said Greece is 
not willing to accept slanderous and unfounded allegations. 
Greece wants to improve Greek-Albanian relations, but that 
improvement depends on respect for the human rights of the Greek 
minority in Albania. 
  Venizelos stressed that if there is any evidence, it should 
have been presented either at the Zurich meeting between Foreign 
Ministers Karolos Papoulias and Alfred Serreqi or at the meeting 
of the Ministries of Public Order delegations in Ioannina. 
  The government appeared satisfied with the explanations made 
by the U.S. State Department, following the demarche lodge by 
Greek Ambassador in Washington Loukas Tsilas, regarding a 
statement by U.S. State Department Spokesman Michael McCurry. 
According to McCurry's statement, the U.S. Government has no 
credible evidence that it is the policy of the Albanian 
Government to suppress the Greek minority. The government 
spokesman said the Greek Government asked the State Department 
to make the explanation given to the Greek ambassador in the 
form of a public statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

