<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Stability Conference Opens in Paris </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    European Stability Conference Opens in Paris </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Turkey's Cetin Comments on European Stability </H4>

<F P=102> TA2705065394 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
2000 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2705065394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has declared that a 
new Europe emerged with the termination of the era of separate 
blocs and it is beneficial to seek solutions for the conflicts 
in Central and Eastern European and (?Baltic) countries. Cetin 
is currently in Paris for the European Stability Pact 
conference, which aims to prevent the ethnic problems in Eastern 
European countries from causing new clashes similar to those in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Cetin replied to reporters' questions. 
  The foreign minister stated that the conference is seeking a 
kind of diplomacy that will avoid conflicts. He said that 
minority and border issues were discussed at first. Stressing 
that disputes must be resolved between neighbors, Cetin remarked 
that countries which will join the European Union [EU] must 
first solve their problems with their neighbors. Greece is such 
an example, Cetin noted, adding: It was admitted into the EU 
without resolving its problems with Turkey and these problems 
are now causing trouble for the EU. 
  Recalling that Turkey solved its problems with Bulgaria in a 
friendly manner, Cetin declared that the clashes in the Caucasus 
constitute a great loss both for the Azerbaijanis and the 
Armenians. 
  The foreign minister, who held meetings with his Russian, 
German, and British counterparts in Paris, also met with French 
Foreign Minister Alain Juppe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

