<H3> <TI>   EU Group To Urge Respect for Human Rights in Algeria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Group To Urge Respect for Human Rights in Algeria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505183594 Paris AFP in English 1728 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2505183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 25 (AFP) -- A high-level European 
Union [EU] team will travel to Algiers on May 30 to call for 
respect for human rights and urge "national dialogue" between 
the government and Islamic fundamentalists, a Belgian Foreign 
Ministry spokesman said Wednesday [25 May]. 
  Greek Deputy Foreign Minister George Papandreou, whose 
country currently chairs the 12-member EU, Belgian Foreign 
Minister Willy Claes, the former chairman and a senior German 
official, representing the next country to chair the 
organisation, were mandated to make the trip by the EU at a 
meeting earlier this month. 
  The representatives will convey a "clear message calling for 
respect for human rights" addressed to all factions in the 
country, the Belgian spokesman said. 
  The EU will also express its satisfaction with a recent 
agreement concluded by Algeria and the International Monetary 
Fund on economic reforms. 
  The EU recently released a second 150 million ECUs (172 
million dollars) of an aid programme frozen since 1991. 

</TEXT>

