<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> The Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Seeks Shared Peacekeeping Costs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Seeks Shared Peacekeeping Costs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2605133194 Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD in Dutch 25 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> BR2605133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ter Beek Wants Money From NATO for </F>
Peacekeeping Duties"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 25 May -- The Netherlands wants financial 
compensation from the other NATO member states for its 
contribution to the peacekeeping operations in Bosnia. The 
countries which are providing soldiers are currently shouldering 
too much of the financial cost of these expensive operations. 
The burden should be divided more fairly. 
  Netherlands Defense Minister Ter Beek made this demand 
yesterday [24 May] in Brussels at the NATO defense ministers' 
meeting. Ter Beek specifically referred to the use of 
Netherlands aircraft to impose the no-fly ban over Bosnia. This 
NATO operation organized under UN auspices, called "Deny 
Flight," involves the United States, the United Kingdom, and 
France, in addition to the Netherlands. These four countries are 
paying the full cost of the operation, between 75 and 80 million 
guilders a year for the Netherlands. 
  The participation of Netherlands soldiers in UN peacekeeping 
missions is paid for by the Development Cooperation Ministry. 
The Netherlands has previously agreed to pay 1.5 percent of the 
cost of all UN operations. 
  But the cost of providing troops and material for NATO 
operations is not divided among all the alliance's member 
states. The presence of forces including a liaison battalion 
and a transport battalion, and the deployment of the Air Force 
(from the northern Italian town of Villafranca to enforce the 
no-fly ban) and the Navy (from the Adriatic Sea) are costing the 
Defense Ministry nearly 140 million guilders in net extra costs. 
Ter Beek has already asked the cabinet for compensation and it 
is possible that this will be provided for in the coming budget. 
  In Brussels, Ter Beek let it be known yesterday that 
"financial solidarity" had to apply within NATO. "The 
Netherlands can not continue writing out blank cheques for 
years. The political signal has been given and now we just have 
to wait to see how it works out," it has been said in 
Netherlands circles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-66013 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu103_b_94002" </HT>


