<DOCNO> FBIS4-66036 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu103_p_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Euro-Vote's Effect on Political Future </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Euro-Vote's Effect on Political Future </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2705113194 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 26 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC2705113194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yeoryios Karelias] </F>
  [Excerpt] What is the most interesting question about the 
12 June European Parliament elections? 
  While it may seem unusual, it is not the percentages of the 
two biggest parties, which are more or less as expected. The 
"unknown factor" is the percentage of the Political Spring 
party, which could be decisive for political developments. 
  A top government official estimates that if Andonios 
Samaras' 
party [Political Spring] gathers a percentage in the double 
digits (last October it gathered almost 5 percent), it will then 
become a regulator in political affairs. 
  There are three reasons for government concern over such a 
possibility: 
  1. It will become more difficult, if not impossible, to 
realize [Prime Minister] Andreas Papandreou's goal of jumping 
over to the Republic's Presidency. 
  2. Elections in the spring of 1995 will be inevitable, as 
Samaras has every reason to seek them. 
  23. The government will be in a very difficult position 
when it comes to accepting a compromise solution on Skopje [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM], as the reaction 
of a reinforced Political Spring cannot be ignored. 
  According to the estimates of government officials, the only 
positive point from a possible big electoral increase for 
Political Spring, is that the conservative faction will finally 
be divided and in that way unable to seek the Presidency. 
"First place for PASOK [Panhellenic Socialist Movement in the 
European Parliament elections] is certain," they said. These 
calculations by government officials are mainly based on the 
(hypothetical) certainty that Samaras' party will cause greater 
damage to New Democracy, while PASOK will be first despite the 
"logical and natural loss" expected by a party in power. A vote 
ranging from 42 to 43 percent is considered a "good result" for 
PASOK. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

