<H3> <TI>   Eurodeputies Reject `Neofascist' Commissioners </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Eurodeputies Reject `Neofascist' Commissioners </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2405141694 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1457 GMT 22 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2405141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union/Italy: Labor </F>
Eurodeputies on `Neofascist Commissioners'"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Brussels, May 22 -- Labor deputies in the 
European Parliament Sunday [22 May] threatened to spark an 
institutional crisis within the European Union [EU] should any 
Italian neofascists be named to the European Commission which is 
to be renewed in January 1995. 
  A communique released here by the Socialist group in the 
European Parliament said that the threat was contained in a 
letter that Labor leader Pauline Green had sent to British 
Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd. In the letter, Green claimed 
that the Labor deputies would refuse to vote for the investiture 
of a new Commission as called for by the Maastricht Treaty, if 
Italian Premier Silvio Berlusconi were to name a neofascist to 
the European Commission. The threatened move is backed by 
Labor's allies in the largest political group in the European 
Parliament, she said, and if carried out would plunge the EU 
immediately into "an unprecedented crisis." 
  The document went on to say that the Commission would be 
politically paralyzed if it did not obtain the approval of the 
only institution within the European Union which was directly 
elected. 
  Green concluded by announcing that Labor deputies and their 
Socialist allies in the European Parliament would refuse to 
cooperate with any fascist minister and would veto any attempt 
to name a neofascist as a Commission member. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

