<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scharping Wants Criticism of FDP Put `in Perspective' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scharping Wants Criticism of FDP Put `in Perspective' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505134494 Hamburg DPA in German 1106 GMT 25 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2505134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mainz -- Rudolf Scharping, chairman of the Social 
Democratic Party [SPD] and minister-president of 
Rhineland-Palatinate, does not expect his criticism of Monday's 
[23 May] presidential election to do his party any harm. He did 
not advocate a direct transition to electing the head of state 
by popular vote, Scharping told journalists in Mainz on 
Wednesday. The implications that such a regulation would have 
for the constitution must be carefully examined, he said. 
  He said he considers the decision made in Berlin to be 
legitimate; but he wanted to point out that the decision was 
based on 1990 election results. Over 800 delegates to the 
Federal Assembly came from parliaments that were elected four 
years ago. The SPD chairman wants to see his fierce criticism of 
the Free Democratic Party [FDP] put in perspective. The comment 
that the FDP is superfluous as a political force of its own only 
referred to the presidential election. At the same time 
Scharping exempted the Rhineland-Palatinate FDP, and thus the 
SPD's coalition partner, from this criticism, saying that they 
have proved to be an independent liberal force in the government 
alliance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

