<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Previti: No Paratroopers for Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Previti: No Paratroopers for Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2605094894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2038 GMT 25 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2605094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rome Willing To Join Rwanda </F>
Efforts, Previti Says"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Brussels, May 25 -- Defense Minister 
Cesare Previti on Wednesday [25 May] confirmed that Italy "is 
ready to join all necessary initiatives" taken by the United 
Nations to stop bloodshed in Rwanda but stressed that "this 
should be taken in a general sense and does not mean we will 
send paratroopers." He did not elaborate. 
  After a series of meetings with his European counterparts 
here, Previti told reporters the foreign policy of the new Rome 
government is aimed at having Italy "catch up" on all fronts, 
"diplomatic and military-humanitarian." He said Italy is still 
"available" should the UN decide to ask for Italian 
peace-keepers in Bosnia and claimed that Italian Armed Forces 
"are capable of responding to calls for peace-keeping 
operations" around the world, as they have in Somalia, 
Mozambique and Lebanon. 
  Following in the footsteps of his three predecessors, 
Previti, too, announced that the Italian Armed Forces will be 
modernized and trimmed down, becoming smaller and more 
efficient. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

