<H3> <TI>   Martino Stresses `Utmost Care' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martino Stresses `Utmost Care' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2505081794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1930 GMT 24 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BR2505081794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rwanda: `Utmost Care' in Assessing </F>
Any Mission, Martino Says"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Washington, May 24 -- The "extremely 
important military and diplomatic implications" of an Italian 
peacekeeping mission to Rwanda "must be studied with the utmost 
care" by the Italian government before any decision is taken, 
Italian Foreign Minister Antonio Martino said at a press 
conference here. 
  Asked to comment on Defence Minister Cesare Previti's 
statement at a Brussels NATO meeting of "general willingness" 
for such a mission, Martino said "I think Previti wanted to 
stress the Italian government's concern for the orphans in 
Rwanda". 
  He added that "nothing precludes" an Italian mission, but 
pointed out that there are "risks of various kinds" attached to 
it. 
  "A decision can only be taken by the government, obviously," 
he said. 

</TEXT>

