<H3> <TI>   Ministers Play Down Fears Over Border With Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministers Play Down Fears Over Border With Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2405103094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2117 GMT 23 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2405103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Croatia/Italy: Fears Over Borders </F>
Unjustified, Ministers Say"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Washington, May 23 -- Both Italian Foreign 
Minister Antonio Martino, here, and Defense Minister Cesare 
Preveti, in Brussels, said on Monday [23 May] that no problem 
existed regarding the borders between Italy and Croatia and that 
fears in this regard, voiced by Croatian president Franjo 
Tudjman, were unjustified. 
  During his press conference here, Foreign Minister Martino 
said "the position adopted by President Tudjman is not justified 
by any attitude or position on our part.... Italy's position is 
that we see absolutely no problem about borders. We have never 
considered treaties to be pieces of paper to be torn up. 
Bilateral questions may exist, obviously, and we hope they can 
be resolved in a friendly way on a bilateral level and which 
satisfies both sides." 
  President Tudjman had said, at the weekend, that die-hard 
Italian fascists had to give up, once and for all, any and all 
claims to coastal provinces of Croatia. 
  Asked whether the treaty of Osimo, which defined the 
Italo-Yugoslav border, could be re-opened, the Italian 
diplomatic chief recalled how Slovenia and Croatia had legally 
replaced Yugoslavia and that the treaty "must be respected and, 
in some cases, even applied." 
  The existing bilateral questions were listed by the minister 
as those regarding the real estate purchases by Italians and 
free circulation of persons. 
  (In Brussels, Defense Minister Preveti said no disputes were 
open between Italy and Croatia and that, at most, only 
adjustments needed to be made which took into account the new 
political reality.) 

</TEXT>

