<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mozambican Delegation Arrives for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mozambican Delegation Arrives for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1905135894 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1231 GMT 19 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1905135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Mozambique/Italy: Government </F>
Delegation in Rome"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 19 -- A Mozambique Government 
delegation led by Transport Minister Guebuza is in Rome for 
meetings with political and parliamentary figures within the 
framework of the intense relations that Rome enjoys both with 
the Maputo government and with Renamo [Mozambique National 
Resistance], the former rebel movement now in the process of 
becoming a bona fide political party. It was Guebuza who 
represented the Maputo government in the negotiations with 
Renamo that led to the signing of a peace pact in Rome in 
October of 1992. 
  The present Rome contacts are aimed at easing the 
implementation of the peace accords and the elections set for 
October 27-28 of this year in Mozambique. 
  During meetings held at the Foreign Ministry here the Maputo 
government reiterated its gratitude to Italy for its 
contribution to the pacification of the African country. 
  Italy, in fact, in addition to helping with the peace 
process, is top contributor to the United Nations fund for 
turning the former Mozambique rebel movement Renamo into a 
political party. 
  The UN special envoy to Mozambique, Aldo Ajello, only 
recently pointed out that the Italian government had given three 
donations totalling 6.28 million dollars, out of a total of 15 
million dollars donated. 
  The fund was set up in May 1993 with the aim of persuading 
Renamo to implement the peace plan signed in Rome in 1992. 
  It was initially to have 10 million dollars; this was later 
raised to 15. 
  The next biggest contributor after Italy is Holland with one 
million dollars, followed by Sweden, South Africa, Switzerland 
and Luxembourg. 
  A second fund to fund campaigns of all Mozambique parties 
for 
October elections will receive donations to the tune of some 
three million dollars, Ajello said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

