<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Meets U.S. Ambassador </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interior Minister Meets U.S. Ambassador </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1905142494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1321 GMT 19 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1905142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "United States/Italy: Maroni Meets </F>
With Ambassador Bartholomew"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 19 -- Italian Interior Minister 
Roberto Maroni met there Thursday [19 May] with United States 
Ambassador Reginald Bartholomew, also in view of President Bill 
Clinton's upcoming visit to Italy, and reiterated how the fight 
against organized crime was a top priority of the new 
government, headed by Premier Silvio Berlusconi. 
  A statement from the Interior Ministry added how Maroni had 
stressed "the validity and appreciation of the Italian 
government for the high level cooperation achieved in the fight 
against organized crime and drug trafficking." 
  "He then underlined" the Ministry note continued, "how one 
of 
the government's top priorities, also to enhance the confidence 
of citizens in the institutions of the democratic state, 
remained the offensive against the mafia, especially in the 
harder hit regions, which will now involve a more incisive role 
by local governments." 
  "Ambassador Bartholomew" the statement added, "renewed the 
high esteem of the FBI and DEA for the significant level of 
professionalism and specialization of Italian law enforcement 
agencies." 
  During today's meeting, the Ministry said, the minister and 
ambassador confirmed the September meeting in Washington of the 
Italian-American committee for collaboration against the mafia, 
terrorism and drug trafficking. 

</TEXT>

