<H3> <TI>   Maroni on Anti-Mafia Efforts, Skinhead Rally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Maroni on Anti-Mafia Efforts, Skinhead Rally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1905093394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2106 GMT 18 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1905093394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Maroni Responds to Senate on Mafia, </F>
Skinheads"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 18 -- Interior Minister Roberto 
Maroni went before the Senate this evening, after the confidence 
vote, to reply to queries put forward concerning recent attacks 
by the mafia in Sicily and last weekend's march in Vicenza of 
neo-Nazi skinheads. 
  Regarding the bombing by the mafia in Piana degli Albanesi, 
which saw the destruction of a home of a Left Democrat party 
official, Maroni replied how he immediately went in person to 
Sicily where he met with seventeen mayors and numerous city 
councilors and private citizens. 
  "The new and effective concept" the interior minister told 
the Senate, "is the that fight against organized crime will now 
take place through local governments which side against the 
mafia phenomenon and are no longer, as once was the case, in 
support of the mafia." 
  Turning his attention to Saturday's [14 May] march in 
Vicenza, Maroni ruled out any fault for the part of National 
Police Chief Vincenzo Parisi and argued that "the ministry 
official, in Rome, who received the request from authorities in 
Vicenza for 80 additional police officers probably did not 
notify Parisi because he underestimated the request." 
  The interior minister then went on to say how the 
participants in the demonstration had all been identified, 
thanks to television tapes, and their names forwarded to 
judicial authorities for violation of laws against fascism. 
Maroni also told the senate how the number of skinheads in 
Italy was 800, of which 300 were considered "activists." 

</TEXT>

