<H3> <TI>   AN Withdraws Bill To Allow Fascist Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AN Withdraws Bill To Allow Fascist Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2005125494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0923 GMT 20 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2005125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bill To Allow Fascist Party </F>
Withdrawn"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 20 -- The bill proposal to modify 
articles of the Constitution which ban the re-organization of 
the Fascist Party and the return of male members of the House of 
Savoy, Italy's former royal family, has been withdrawn. 
  The bill had been presented at the start of the new 
legislature by the National Alliance, born form the neo-fascist 
MSI [Italian Social Movement]. The MSI traditionally presented 
such a proposal at the start of each legislature, but its 
presentation by the National Alliance [AN] raised an outcry 
given that the National Alliance had promised that it was 
"post-fascist" when entering the government coalition. 
  The withdrawal of the request had been pre-announced by 
National Alliance leader Gianfranco Fini and was presented by 
Vincenzo Trantino, of the National Alliance, also on behalf of 
the bill's original sponsors. 
  The government of Premier Silvio Berlusconi has been under 
pressure from both the Left opposition at home and its European 
partners for the presence in the executive of five ministers 
from the National Alliance branded as neo-fascist. Repeated 
calls had been made, in fact, for members of the National 
Alliance to repudiate fascist ideology. 
  The MSI, Italian Social Movement, was formed by members of 
Mussolini's end-of-the-war Italian Social Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

