<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Poll Examines Berlusconi Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    French Poll Examines Berlusconi Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1805114194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1737 GMT 17 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1805114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "France/Italy: Berlusconi in French </F>
Poll"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Paris, May 17 -- Some 54 percent of the 
French feel that Italy's European Union [EU] partners should 
boycott the hard-right National Alliance ministers in Prime 
Minister Silvio Berlusconi's cabinet and half see the new 
premier as a "populist demagogue," but 48 percent believe the 
Berlusconi phenomenon could be repeated in France, according to 
a poll published by the French Catholic weekly, LA VIE. 
  The poll indicated that 68 percent of the sample see a 
"significant" risk of a growth in neo-fascism in Europe, and 
only 26 percent believe there is no such risk. Italy's National 
Alliance, which has five ministers in the Berlusconi government, 
was known until earlier this year as the Italian Social 
Movement, the post-war heir to Benito Mussolini's Fascist Party. 
  According to the LA VIE poll, only 28 percent of the sample 
believe the EU should impose no boycott on the Alliance 
ministers and 18 percent had no opinion, just as many as denied 
that Berlusconi is a "populist demagogue." 
  But even if many French are critical of Berlusconi's 
political style, as many as 37 percent believe he may have the 
qualities to get Italy back on the rails. Thirty percent 
disagreed with this suggestion. The poll suggested that 36 
percent of the sample believe the Berlusconi phenomenon would be 
impossible in France, while 16 percent didn't know. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

