Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comino Fears Italy May Not Meet Maastricht Criteria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comino Fears Italy May Not Meet Maastricht Criteria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2005104294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1637 GMT 19 
May 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2005104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Italy Risks </F>
Missing Maastricht Deadlines"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, May 19 -- The new Italian minister for 
European Union affairs, Domenico Comino of the Northern League, 
voiced his concern Thursday [19 May] that Italy may not be able 
to meet the 1996 deadlines set in the Maastricht Treaty on 
European Union [EU] for economic integration. 
  In a meeting with the press to illustrate his ministerial 
game plan, Comino, 39, recalled how his position had no 
negotiation powers and thus he saw his task more of one to 
coordinate the actions of the other ministries in a European 
Union framework. 
  Comino went on to suggest adopting a "blue stamp" to be 
applied to measures taken by Parliament which are in line with 
European Union regulations and laws. In this way, he observed, 
his office would not have to dedicate 50 percent of its time 
trying to resolve conflicts between Italy and the European Union 
which much of the time are born from conflicts between laws and 
regulations more than Italy's failure to adopt EU laws. 
  The minister then went on to suggest the creation of 
"trans-national socio-economic areas" which would serve as a 
link in the European Union decision-making process during the 
initial stage, when precise projects are drawn up. 
  Comino also stressed the need for Italy to play a more 
leading role in the European Union, "a more qualified presence," 
with less emphasis on its presence in the bureaucratic apparatus. 
  Asked to comment on the reaction of Italy's European Union 
partners to the presence in the Rome executive of ministers from 
the National Alliance, the rightist party born from the 
neo-fascist MSI [Italian Social Movement], Comini replied 
"Foreign Minister Martino has already re-assured the Europeans" 
and that on this question "there has been a lot of exploitation 
by many sides." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-66143 </DOCNO>
